At the same time, Brazil is a country marked by intense social debate and inequality. While the majority of the population leans toward conservative values regarding the protection of life from conception, there is also a significant national discourse regarding public health, the risks of clandestine procedures, and the difficult circumstances faced by many women. Because the prevailing cultural sentiment remains anchored in religious and traditional family-oriented values, while recognizing the complexity of the circumstances in which these cases occur, the perspective is generally cautious and leans toward the lower end of the scale.

